column26:
Hello, my name is Charley Heeran. I am 16 years old and I have been Acting for four years.
Some other things that I enjoy are rollerblading snowboarding, skateboarding doing stunts,
drawing and building. One of my other major hobbies is filmmaking. I originally got into Acting
because I watched the show Stranger Things. I really enjoyed all the elements of it both Acting
wise and camera technique. I love being around other actors and other filmmakers. It helps me
expand my knowledge on my craft and I get to learn about how other people do things with their
art. For me auditioning is the highlight of my day. I really enjoy evaluating characters and getting
to play them out how I think that they would react in the real world. I have been on set a few
times for a couple different projects and each time has been a wonderful memory that I get to
cherish. I have been in Acting school for four years now. I attend in Acting school every Monday
in Long Island, New York. It’s called actor’s garage and I have a wonderful acting coach and
wonderful friends there. I love Acting because everybody is so supportive of each other. my
favorite thing to celebrate in humans is kindness, and I truly believe the film industry embraces
that

column26:
Caroline Vartanian—a Union Armenian actor with dual citizenship, currently splitting her time between two of North America’s most exciting markets: Los Angeles and Toronto.

This year has been such a pivotal one for Caroline. Over the summer, she filmed a recurring role in Netflix’s upcoming series Vladimir, opposite Rachel Weisz. She was originally booked for one episode, but after my first day on set, the showrunner singled Caroline out (in front of everyone) and invited her personally to read for another role—ultimately deciding to rewrite my original character into the storyline! That recognition grew into a recurring arc she just wrapped filming last month.
In addition, she completed Forbidden Fruits, a Universal/IFC feature film directed by Meredith Alloway and starring Lili Reinhart and Lola Tung, slated for a Spring 2026 theatrical release (read here). Other recent work includes a Paramount+ commercial with Renee Rapp (watch here), and a National McDonald’s campaign which I just wrapped! 
Her past credits include Disney Channel’s Original Spin, CBC’s Pretty Hard Cases, and the interactive feature Lydia, in which I played the title role.
Outside of acting, she bring a strong physical background as a trained dancer, gymnast, aerialist, and Worlds-level competitive cheerleader, with professional circus training from the Toronto School of Circus Arts. That foundation allows her to bring a fearless physicality and precision to her on-screen work—something that’s become part of her signature. Caroline continue to train at LB Acting Studio, Armstrong Acting Studios, and KH Casting for voiceover, where she has found a real passion for VO work as well.
With dual citizenship, both valid U.S. and Canadian passports, and housing in both cities, she fully flexible and ready to work wherever opportunity calls. Fluent in English and Armenian, and can authentically portray a broad range of backgrounds and ages.

Thank you so much for your time and consideration.
https://youtu.be/x93IlAH03qA

column26:
Dear Agents, 
I am so grateful for this opportunity!
This summer I was in a Pure Flix series that will be airing on Amazon Prime, appeared in two commercials, and I’m excited to transition to film. I am currently studying acting with Kia Riddick-Taylor, and have been coached by John D’Aquino in LA and Jim Brasswell from the American Idol Experience at Disney. As well, I attended a seminar with Jack Griffo (Max Thunderman- Nickelodeon). I have learned a lot of great things during these lessons and can’t wait to put them into practice! In addition to acting, I’m a soprano singer and train with Betsy Hammer, who is located in LA. I enjoy dancing Jazz, Tap and Hip Hop, horseback riding, swimming, and skateboarding.
My family is very supportive of my dream and is willing to help me travel.
Thank you! Can’t wait to hear from you!
Best regards,
Chloe Harris
